<TEXT>
neon and videotape have replaced oils and 
watercolors at an art exhibit devoted exclusively to computers 
more than 50 works by computer artists from around the world went 
on display friday at the computer museum the art including two 
and three dimensional works kinetic sculpture animation and 
polydimensional works on videotape runs until september 
among the works the 144 neon lights that form san francisco 
artist karl x hausers wallofish and new york artist lillian 
schwartzs chromeplated mobile capricious constellation 
the one thing all these pieces have in common is that theyve 
been created by both humans and computers said museum spokeswoman 
gail jennes 
the exhibit titled computer art in context is part of a 
conference on computer graphics sponsored by siggraph one of the 
worlds leading professional associations of computer graphics 
researchers and practitioners 
hauser 34 a glass blower by trade arranged his neon work with 
the use of a computer that controls the lighting and shape of the 
design 
schwartz designed her giant mobile capricious constellation 
with the help of scientist arno penzias who won the nobel prize for 
physics in 1978 the mobile is driven by a computer programmed to 
move it at random as if blown by winds 
the computer museum officials say theirs is the only museum in 
the world devoted exclusively to computers and their impact on 
society it includes 60 permanent exhibits an animation theater and 
a multimedia robot show 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

