<TEXT>
police arrested at least seven striking eastern 
pilots and employees friday as they stopped their cars in a baggage 
area at atlantas big airport on one of its busiest days 
it is a grassroots movement said hank weber a spokesman for 
the eastern pilots union in miami some disgruntled eastern 
strikers including nonunion people are trying to show their 
frustration 
those arrested were charged with misdemeanors disobeying an 
officer and impeding the flow of traffic and nearly all of the 
arrested were pulled from cars at an eastern baggage area at 
hartsfieldatlanta international airport 
other strikers gathered signatures on petitions that called for a 
continued boycott of the airline which has been crippled by a 
fourmonth strike 
we asked them to move along but they wanted to shut down this 
airport said police maj wb shannon this was an obvious 
attempt by the union to hurt the citizens of atlanta we dont like 
it and were not going to take it 
airport spokesman john braden said friday was one of the busiest 
days in hartsfields history with about 140000 travelers passing 
through the airport 
in new jersey about 300 eastern strikers and supporters marched 
on friday to newark international airport and blocked evening 
rushhour traffic heading to the terminal of continental airlines 
easterns sister airline 
about 50 police wearing riot gear and holding night sticks tried 
to keep the crowd moving through the airports roads and another 50 
tried to control fridays rush hour traffic there was no violence 
and no arrests were reported 
the intent is to tell everyone in the whole world that 
easterns still on strike said ed borowick president of local 
1445 of the international association of machinists 
borowick said the union was under a courtordered limit of 15 
pickets per entrance but marchers took over the four traffic lanes 
where passengers debark to get to continentals departure counters 
for about an hour 
similar plans to greet miami travelers with airport slowdowns 
failed to materialize a few strikers drove slowly through miami 
international airport but they were moved along by special police 
teams 
in new york easterns boss frank lorenzo warned that striking 
pilots who might want to come back to work likely will find theyve 
already been bumped from their jobs 
were not dependent on the pilots coming back by any means 
said lorenzo chairman of easterns parent company texas air corp 
pilots union officials were to meet this weekend with management 
and easterns courtappointed bankruptcy examiner for talks on a 
contract agreement to end their walkout against the company 
weber said the slowdown wasnt sanctioned by easterns unions 
which mark four months on strike july 4 but strikers from the 
pilots flight attendants and machinists unions said they would 
drive their cars slowly through airport terminal areas on friday 
afternoon and possibly next tuesday 
ron gunther operations director at miami international airport 
said extra police officers and tow trucks were called out to lessen 
traffic tieups he said holiday travelers should leave an hour or 
so earlier than usual to allow for possible delays 
if the unions pull off this blockadetype activity my reaction 
would be theyre making the traveling public the innocent victims in 
a labormanagement dispute eastern spokesman robin matell said 
eastern meanwhile was gearing up for a tripling of its daily 
schedule with 79 daily flights this week eastern was set to hit 
226 daily flights beginning sunday 
we have to see whether they can make the announced schedule and 
whether they can sustain it for seven days weber said watch 
for cancelled flights they dont have enough pilots 
the carrier has been operating less than 10 percent of its 
prestrike schedule of around 1000 flights a day since the strike 
that started march 4 it filed for chapter 11 bankruptcy 
reorganization on march 9 and says it will rebuild as a smaller 
airline 
in an interview friday lorenzo said any returning strikers would 
find most of the available jobs at the new scaleddown eastern were 
taken up by the 500 or so new hires and 300 who crossed picket lines 
who already are working and by other pilots who will complete 
training in the weeks ahead 
eastern also is near agreement with creditors over its plan to 
emerge from bankruptcy court protection as a scaleddown carrier 
that would require only about 1700 pilots to operate by december at 
its target level of around twothirds of its prestrike size that 
compares with the 3600 that flew the prestrike version 
the unions are backing a buyout bid for eastern led by chicago 
commodities trader joseph ritchie 
