<TEXT>
president bush marking the 25th anniversary of 
the civil rights act of 1964 says he will be satisfied with 
nothing less than equality of opportunity for all americans 
including 36 million who have disabilities 
while celebrating our achievements and recommitting ourselves 
to their preservations we must recognize that the full promise of 
the civil rights movement has still not been achieved he told 200 
civil rights leaders at a white house ceremony friday 
the hard lesson of the passing years is that it has not been 
enough to wage a war against the old forms of bigotry and 
inequality the president said before flying off for a long 
holiday weekend in maine 
bush called on congress to join me in a new partnership to 
reauthorize the civil rights commission with a goal of launching a 
renewed civil rights mission 
the commissions sixyear authorization expires nov 30 
civil rights leaders jesse jackson martin luther king iii 
benjamin hooks vernon jordan and james farmer attended the ceremony 
the landmark civil rights law was signed by president lyndon b 
johnson on july 2 1964 the act banned segregation in public 
accommodations and paved the way for court action to end bias in 
hiring and promotions 
also in the audience was rosa parks whose defiant refusal to 
move to the back of a montgomery ala bus on dec 1 1955 was an 
early milestone in the civil rights movement 
bush said the gathering was not only to commemorate an 
anniversary but to celebrate a movement and to rededicate our 
efforts to the unfinished work of that movement 
however some civil rights leaders say recent supreme court 
decisions restricting affirmative action and making it more 
difficult to prove discrimination in the workplace have hurt the 
civil rights movement 
there was more damage done to civil rights statutes in the last 
2 weeks than in the last 2 decades said ralph neas executive 
director of the leadership conference on civil rights 
bush did not directly address civil rights leaders concerns but 
called for vigilant and aggressive enforcement of civil rights 
and said his administration wont tolerate discrimination 
jackson told reporters that justice had become more expensive 
more distant and less likely to come because of the high court 
rulings 
