<TEXT>
attorney general dick thornburgh has decided 
that a member of the irish republican army should be deported to the 
united kingdom where he has been convicted and sentenced to life in 
prison for killing a british soldier 
thornburgh overruled an immigration appeals board finding that 
joseph patrick thomas doherty could reopen proceedings to seek 
political asylum 
but doherty cannot be deported immediately because of a pending 
legal challenge to a 1988 deportation order by thenattorney general 
edwin meese iii said justice department spokesman david runkel 
the challenge is pending before the 2nd us circuit court of 
appeals in new york 
in my discretion i would not grant the respondent asylum 
thornburgh said it is the policy of the united states that those 
who commit acts of violence against a democratic state should 
receive prompt and lawful punishment 
deporting doherty to the united kingdom would unquestionably 
advance this important policy thornburgh wrote 
the state department had previously determined that deporting 
doherty is in the foreign policy interests of this country 
the doherty case has been the focus of political controversy 
particularly among a group of house members from new york city who 
contend he should be treated as political refugee 
dohertys supporters were upset by thornburghs decision 
rep eliot l engell dny said it was an outrage that flies 
in the face of american justice 
its morally legally and politically indefensible said 
peter king republican comptroller of nassau county in the suburbs 
of new york city thornburgh is allowing the justice department 
and the american legal system to be an accessory to margaret 
thatchers british government 
sen orrin hatch rutah has also urged thornburgh to grant 
dohertys request for political asylum 
doherty 34 was convicted of killing a british army captain 
during a 1980 ambush of british troops in ulster he escaped from a 
prison in belfast the next year and was arrested in new york city in 
1983 he has been held in federal custody since then 
thornburgh overruled a nov 14 board of immigration appeal ruling 
that doherty could reopen his request for political asylum 
the immigration and naturalization service began deportation 
proceedings in 1984 after a federal judge in brooklyn ny ruled 
doherty could not be extradited because his crime was a political 
act that made him eligible for asylum 
</TEXT>
