<DOCNO> AP890701-0034 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
soviet citizens looking for books at the 
moscow library where lenin dostoyevsky and chekhov once studied 
will soon be using computers programmed at a virginia university 
virginia tech library systems president vinod chachra sees it as 
more than a technical challenge to computerize the card catologue of 
the massive lenin library the project will encourage the soviet 
policy of openness or glasnost and help further business relations 
between the superpowers he says 
this is really opening up access to information chachra 
said in one sense this is bringing in more equality with the 
technology by automating the system it greatly increases the 
access to all people 
chachras company which is controlled by a nonprofit arm of 
virginia tech announced last month that the soviets had chosen its 
software system to automate their national library chachra will 
meet with the librarys director nikolai semyonovich kartashov in 
blacksburg on july 18 to discuss the start of the project in 
november 
the work is expected to take up to four years and cost 1 
million he said 
the lenin library located just off red square has 35 million 
books in 247 languages and 3000 employees its 18 reading rooms 
many of them with ornate high ceilings and lit by chandeliers seat 
more than 2300 people and are visited by more than 7000 readers 
each day 
in comparison the library of congress in washington has 26 
million books and the new york public library has 6 million books 
chachra said 
the library was founded in 1862 as the rumiantsev library named 
after a count whose collection accounted for most of its original 
holdings it was renamed in 1925 after the father of the russian 
revolution 
in addition to lenin famous russians who have studied in the 
library include authors leo tolstoy fyodor dostoyevsky and anton 
chekhov 
chachra visited the library during a recent fiveday trip to 
moscow 
i was struck by the number of people waiting outside the door 
for the library to open he said there arent that many 
libraries in the soviet union the users are dedicated 
they have to be checking out a book is a lengthy and frustrating 
process and just finding the right card catalog file is an ordeal 
because there are separate catalogs for various subcollections 
chachra said 
after finding the right catalogue the user must write the title 
and author on a slip of paper and stand in line for up to an hour to 
give the note to a circulation clerk the clerk sends the note to 
the book retrieval area via pneumatic tubes 
it can take anywhere from a half a day to five days to get a 
book chachra said occasionally the book has been lent to 
someone else and after waiting that long you find out you cant get 
it anyway 
under the planned automated system people looking for a book 
will step up to a usmade computer running on software designed by 
chachra and his staff for many it will be their first experience 
with a personal computer chachra said 
users will be able to make a book request directly from a 
terminal and find out right away whether the book is checked out 
chachra said 
the current system restricts access to information because of its 
cumbersome nature chachra said but that will change 
by the nature of the technology it will be in favor of the 
user he said the software is designed for open access 
chachra said it remains to be seen whether soviet officials will 
give access to some books that are now off limits to users 
presumably for political reasons 
the lenin library will be the first soviet library to 
computerize but it will be the sixth national library to automate 
with software from virginia tech library systems the company has 
computerized the national gallery of art library and the national 
agricultural library in the united states as well as libraries in 
scotland malaysia and finland 
the company has computerized nearly 100 other libraries 
including that of the us supreme court 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

