<TEXT>
the humble mussel a tidal water 
delicacy is now playing a pivotal role in monitoring pollution in 
the north sea 
spread over 15 locations along the dutch coast 1500 of the 
jetblack mollusks were put into service this week as a way 
scientists can check the flow of poisonous waste through the north 
sea one of the most heavily polluted basins in the world a project 
spokesman said friday 
in filtering algae from sea water for food the bivalves also 
store poisonous waste and heavy metals a look at what they have 
stored gives a picture of the quality of water they live in 
they give us a perfect overview of the water quality over the 
time span involved said martin scholten a spokesman for the 
government project 
the mussels live in plastic baskets attached to shipping buoys up 
to six miles off the coast they will be checked in three sixweek 
periods over a year at a cost of 113600 
mussels are ideal for this kind of job because they filter so 
much water scholten said the average mussel processes about 13 
gallons of sea water a day he said 
