following a special mass at nearby st vitus cathedral celebrating 
the roman catholic leaders 90th birthday 
long live our cardinal the crowd chanted as tomasek appeared 
on the balcony overlooking the square we want religious freedom 
czechoslovakia is the only soviet bloc country where communist 
authorities have for decades blocked the appointment of religious 
leaders for many of the countrys 13 dioceses 
tomasek is a strong advocate of less state supervision of church 
affairs church officials estimate that half of czechoslovakias 15 
million people are catholic 
earlier about 8000 people from across czechoslovakia filled st 
vitus cathedral for the mass also attending were highranking roman 
catholic clergy from the vatican poland hungary west germany and 
other nations foreign dignitaries included us ambassador julian 
m niemczyk 
during the mass a special envoy from the vatican read a letter 
from pope john paul ii applauding tomaseks work 
john paul praised tomasek for all that you have patiently 
endured and for devoting himself to the defense of the rights of 
the church and of mankind according to the letter read by italian 
archbishop francesco colassuono 
the popes letter also mentioned tomaseks pain and exile 
during his career an apparent reference to tomaseks 195154 
internment in a labor camp after a communist crackdown on religion 
in a short address tomasek stressed the importance of the church 
in czechoslovakia only christ can give an answer to the hunger of 
our minds for truth and to the thirst of our hearts for love 
tomasek said at the mass 
on the square some political activists circulated a human rights 
petition that has angered communist authorities 
the petition demands the right to hold political demonstrations 
freedom for all political prisoners and a reassessment by communist 
authorities of the 1968 prague spring reforms which were crushed by 
a sovietled invasion that year 
communist authorities have hinted that the signatories might be 
disciplined for their initiative the communist party newspaper rude 
pravo on saturday called the petition an appeal to disrupt the 
republic 
