<TEXT>
new york citys famed five boroughs could 
someday become four 
the legislature working into early saturday morning in an 
endofsession marathon voted to give staten island residents a 
chance to say whether they want to secede from new york city 
if gov mario cuomo signs the bill residents of the smallest 
borough might be able to vote in november 1990 on whether to take a 
bite out the big apple cuomo said saturday he hadnt decided what 
to do 
polls say staten island residents overwhelmingly favor secession 
an issue tied up with a courtmandated restructuring of the largest 
us city government 
we didnt start out with the idea of leaving the city said 
state sen john marchi a staten island republican we just wanted 
to maintain our voice in the city we didnt have anything against 
the city of new york i ran for mayor there twice 
the secession movement gathered steam after the us supreme 
court ruled in march that the board of estimate which governs city 
spending and construction was unconstitutional because it gave 
staten islands 400000 residents equal representation to the more 
populous boroughs such as brooklyn with more than 2 million people 
staten island residents fear the city charter revision 
commissions plan for revamping city government will shortchange 
their borough 
it would reduce us really to colonial status marchi said 
cuomo said he believed the legislators action was not an 
approval of secession but simply a political statement what they 
are saying is staten island ought to be protected cuomo said he 
shared those sympathies but wasnt sure how to go about providing 
such protection 
cuomo is from queens manhattan and the bronx are the other two 
boroughs 
residents of staten island have never considered themselves true 
new york city residents said elizabeth connelly a staten island 
democrat who shepherded the secession bill through the state 
assembly 
she noted though that the boroughs more upstate character has 
lessened since the verrazanonarrows bridge linked it with brooklyn 
and it began absorbing people fleeing high housing costs and other 
urban woes in other boroughs 
many leaders from the other boroughs including mayor edward i 
koch a manhattanite fear the loss of tax revenue to the city if 
staten island secedes 
lawmakers who opposed the bill also argued that all new york city 
residents should have the right to decide if part of the city should 
break away 
its fundamentally unfair to all the other residents of the 
city of new york said assemblyman anthony genovesi a 
powerful brooklyn democrat i dont think that anyone has 
considered the ramification of how it all works out 
connelly argues that staten island residents never had a say in 
the 1898 decision by the legislature that made the island a borough 
of new york city 
the 1989 bill calls for staten island voters to decide two 
questions whether staten island should break from new york city and 
whether it should form a county or city type of government the 
legislation wont allow a secession vote unless a charter revision 
is voted on in a citywide referendum this november 
even if the secession decision is a long way off and by no means 
a certainty its already unifying a borough thats been the butt of 
jokes marchi said 
there is a lot of excitement he said im telling you it 
doesnt make any difference rich or poor black or white fat or 
skinny it doesnt make any difference 
</TEXT>
