<TEXT>
provisions of a new utah law prohibiting 
cigarette vending machines were put on hold by a federal judge less 
than 12 hours before the law was to have taken effect saturday 
us district senior judge aldon janderson issued a temporary 
restraining order banning enforcement of the challenged section of 
the law after an emergency hearing friday 
sales until this matter is resolved will be the same as under 
the old law anderson ruled 
four vendingmachine companies had filed suit against the state 
friday morning requesting that the adolescent tobacco prevention 
act passed by this years legislature be declared unconstitutional 
andersons ruling prevents the vendingmachine provision of the 
law from taking effect for at least 10 days 
the vending machine ban which won widespread support from 
lawmakers is aimed in part at curbing uncontrolled access to 
cigarettes by minors it would prohibit all cigarette 
vendingmachine sales except in bars private clubs or offices and 
other work areas not open to the public 
a second hearing was scheduled for july 7 to determine whether a 
preliminary injunction should be issued until the laws 
constitutionality can be tested 
the plaintiffs claim a ban on vending machines will drive them 
out of business without restricting sales to minors any more than 
current law which already requires employees of businesses having 
cigarette machines to check customers ages before enabling the 
machines to work by remote switch 
the restraining order presented no threat of change in the sale 
of cigarettes to minors since a cashier must still check the age 
of the person buying cigarettes anderson said 
the judge made his decision despite the states claim the lawsuit 
is not a proper question for a federal court 
we do not feel there is a constitutional issue and therefore 
the plaintiffs cannot prevail on the merits said assistant 
attorney general linda luinstra who argued the case involved 
questions that should be challenged in a state court 
but plaintiffs lawyer richard rappaport said the law deprives 
his clients of business without any rationale 
there is a public interest in having children not smoke he 
said theres no public interest in having adults buying 
cigarettes handtohand over the counter instead of having adults 
buy cigarettes from a machine after the business owner determines 
they are adults 
over the past week and before fridays ruling many of utahs 
vending machine companies were busy removing cigarette machines from 
restaurants hotels and other public places in anticipation of the 
new law 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

