<TEXT>
when martin alsobrooks was hired as an 
animal technician at a research laboratory here nobody told him the 
monkeys hed handle likely would carry a virus that could kill him 
less than three months later one of his coworkers is dead a 
former coworker is hospitalized and alsobrooks and about 30 current 
or former colleagues are on an experimental antiviral drug they 
hope will stem the rare disease in case they too have been 
infected 
the herpes b virus better known as the monkey virus is found in 
more than 50 percent of rhesus monkeys a type of macaque the virus 
is harmless to the animals but more than half of the 30 cases 
documented in humans since the disease was first reported 57 years 
ago have been fatal its commonly transmitted through bites and 
scratches 
i try not to worry about things i have no control over but my 
family is worried my mother is lighting candles said alsobrooks 
33 whose blood test results were inconclusive 
thousands of these monkeys are being used daily in laboratory 
experiments nationwide while progress is being made in the area of 
animal welfare rights the conditions in which lab employees work 
are largely unregulated by federal or state law 
officials at international research and development corp say 
they have complied strictly with guidelines set by the centers for 
disease control in atlanta and that the two technicians who were 
infected did not report their wounds 
tom mcgeorge a 23yearold technician died june 20 just a few 
days after the virus was diagnosed the hospitalized former 
employee whose name is being withheld is in serious condition he 
worked at the company only one week before quitting this spring 
early detection was impossible since neither man reported his 
injuries which is required by the company said francis x wazeter 
iii irdc vice president 
when an employee reports being bitten or scratched by a monkey a 
disinfectant is promptly applied to the wound to kill the virus 
wazeter said 
some employees said bites and scratches were so common and the 
pressure to complete studies so great that it was nearly impossible 
to report each wound to the company nurse 
wazeter denied there was pressure on employees to work fast and 
said reporting wounds is mandatory he also denied allegations by 
several employees that the leather gloves used by monkey handlers 
part of the extensive protection gear usually had holes and took 
months to replace 
the cdcs guidelines which are not enforced by any regulatory 
agency were created two years ago after a herpes b outbreak in 
pensacola fla killed two monkey handlers and infected two other 
people 
some current and former employees at the lab believe a high 
turnover rate poor training and heavy workloads played a part in 
the outbreak of the rare disease which has been documented only 30 
times since the first case was reported in 1932 said dr gary 
holmes a cdc epidemiologist 
the disease which attacks the brain and central nervous system 
frequently leads to encephalitis an inflammation of the brain and 
then to death since the virus has been documented 16 of the 24 
patients who have shown symptoms have died holmes said in one case 
in pensacola the virus was spread persontoperson 
of about 135 blood tests conducted on current and former irdc lab 
employees who had contact with the monkeys in the last two months 
81 were negative and five were inconclusive michigan department of 
public health officials said the rest of the results are expected 
this week 
the company which employs 350 people does animal research for 
medical pharmaceutical veterinary and agricultural companies 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

