fire officials were focusing their investigation saturday on 
whether extensive electrical work being done in the building played 
a role in the fire and whether some of that work violated city codes 
perrin said an electrical contractor received a city permit in 
may to renovate the first floor but fire investigators found 
evidence of largescale work on the sixth and other floors 
there were ladders in there and they had heavy conduit pulled 
out he said such work without a permit would be a violation 
he said 
the building is managed by american management co of the los 
angeles suburb of torrance harry komsky vice president of the 
company said an investigation would begin into the fire but he 
would not comment on the lack of sprinklers 
komsky said the company is shocked beyond words at the loss of 
life and the injuries 
six federal agencies have offices in the building located north 
of midtown atlanta including the department of agriculture 
department of the treasury department of health and human services 
and the national transportation safety board 
none of those offices is on the sixth floor where the damage was 
the worst and where the people were trapped perrin said 
perrin said he hoped the fire would result in legislation 
requiring sprinkler systems in all buildings beyond a certain 
height regardless of their ages he said he planned to send 
information about the blaze to congressmen interested in fire safety 
issues 
there were reports by some agencies friday that a fifth person 
had died in the fire but martin said that stemmed from confusion 
over the unrelated death of a construction worker who fell from a 
construction site a few miles away at about the same time as the 
fire 
