<TEXT>
while millions of americans twirl sparklers set off firecrackers 
and ooh and aah over fourth of july fireworks displays us 
importers are getting headaches worrying about future festivities 
there certainly is considerable concern for the 1990 season 
says john conkling executive director of the american pyrotechnics 
association everybody is awaiting word from factories in china 
about the status of future deliveries 
so before the last wisp of smoke has cleared on july 4 many 
fireworks firms will have placed next years orders in anticipation 
of a possible shortage due to chinas precarious political and 
economic situation 
the chinese credited with inventing fireworks about 1000 years 
ago make the bulk more than 75 percent of the stuff us 
consumers use during independence day celebrations 
giving people such fleeting thrills as they get from lighting 
roman candles takes us companies months of planning negotiating 
and waiting for shipments even in the best of circumstances 
us fireworks firms normally have their overseas ordering done 
by the autumn of each year to allow enough time for foreign 
factories to manufacture and ship the goods early enough for 
distribution in the united states before july 
now however the uncertainty of chinese supplies has companies 
scrambling to keep from being caught short next fourth of july by 
far the biggest time of year for the fireworks business 
current supplies should be enough to satisfy this seasons 
demand most imported chinese fireworks had already arrived in the 
united states or left chinas shores before the beijing governments 
bloody crackdown on prodemocracy activists 
the shipments for this year started arriving in the united 
states back in november of 1988 observed john d rogers a 
fireworks expert at the consumer product safety commission so the 
majority of them were already here or on the water 
