<TEXT>
recessions or economic downturns of the kind 
wall street is now worrying about have a terrible and welldeserved 
reputation but is there anything nice to be said about them 
lots they remove excesses like severe inventory pileups from the 
economy they remind sellers that the consumer is still boss they 
might even be accompanied by or cause lower prices and borrowing 
rates 
what they do best perhaps is remind both sellers and buyers 
that the old law of supply and demand is still on the books in boom 
times the seller usually has the upper hand in bad times the 
consumer ascends 
this pervasive impact may have shown up already in lower housing 
and stock prices and it could make even bigger inroads into the 
automobile market which for a year has been fighting its own 
private battle with a slowdown 
the automotive market in fact has been a display case of the 
strategies that come into play when the demandsupply balance is 
changing demand for cars has been ebbing for at least a year 
supply however has remained high 
under such conditions the suppliers must make concessions which 
they did in the form of rebates and belowmarket borrowing rates 
while the federal reserve attempted to ease the economy into a 
slower pace by raising borrowing rates the automakers sought to 
challenge them by lowering their own rates 
it was a battle the automakers were destined to lose because the 
fed had the ultimate power it had the option of raising rates until 
it won its way the automakers in contrast could lower their rates 
to zero but not beyond 
conceding defeat the automakers have sharply reduced production 
in an attempt to restore sellerbuyer balance scheduled output for 
july is at an annual rate of 5 million units or roughly half the 
annual selling rate 
the question now is whether the balance can be restored in time 
to avoid price cutting if demand remains low the possibility 
exists that companies may be unable to reduce inventories 
sufficiently before new models are announced if so more automobile 
bargains might be available consumers will have won 
over the past year housing has also demonstrated the power of 
supply and demand demand was down due to high prices and interest 
rates in response and despite a recent and probably temporary 
upturn prices stagnated or fell 
a housing market of that sort is a warning to makers of 
appliances furniture and other items associated with housing such 
as lawn products to lower their inventories or else be forced to 
lower their prices 
if a recession does develop and there is still no proof that one 
will there could other consumer benefits 
credit card issuers for example have clung to high interest 
rates some of them charging more than 20 percent preferring 
instead to attract customers through contests lowcost merchandise 
travel discounts and the like 
however such incentives lose their drawing power when people are 
in a recession mode waiting and watching their dollars the biggest 
incentive in such an atmosphere might be lower interest charges 
sellers of nonessential purchases might be forced to win 
customers through price cuts among them are airlines resorts 
hotels various entertainment outlets and restaurants all of which 
have been raising prices 
eating out for example already has suffered a hit as economist 
edward yardeni points out from 1982 to 1987 restaurant meal sales 
rose from 1129 billion a year to 1334 billion a year they 
peaked at a 139 billion rate in january of this year by may the 
rate was down 14 percent to 132 billion 
when restaurateurs see figures such as these they know what must 
be done cut prices true they have the option of dramatically 
improving the quality of food and service but in a recession price 
cuts are much better 
price cuts are nice but not the recession that produces them 
most people it seems safe to say without a survey would opt for 
expansion and pay raises instead 
that leads to the ultimate good thing to be said about a 
recession it is the base for the next expansion for more jobs 
higher pay and lots of spending options 
