<TEXT>
investors have been pouring money into junkbond 
mutual funds in recent months as interest rates available elsewhere 
have fallen but they may be unaware of the danger lurking in these 
tempting highyield investments 
many people hear the word bonds and they think safe 
conservative said neal litvack of fidelity investments operator 
of one of the largest junkbond funds junk bonds have a tendency 
to dance to a different drummer 
that drummer is the state of the economy unlike investmentgrade 
corporate bonds junk bonds face a greater danger of plummeting in 
price in a recession 
junk bonds are bonds that carry a low credit rating as determined 
by creditrating agencies their low rating reflects the fact that 
the companies that issued the bonds may be deep in debt or otherwise 
poor credit risks 
junk bonds also are used to raise cash for many leveraged 
takeovers where the corporate raider takes on a great deal of debt 
in order to pay for the target company 
in contrast investmentgrade corporate bonds are considered a 
conservative safe investment because the issuing company is rated 
financially sound and considered able to meet its debt obligations 
even in a downturn 
to make up for their extra risk junk bonds pay a higher interest 
rate junk bond mutual funds have been yielding 12 percent or more 
recently compared with about 9 percent for investmentgrade bond 
funds and 8 percent for treasury bond funds 
litvack said the assets of fidelitys junkbond mutual fund 
surged from 17 billion at the end of march to about 2 billion 
last week 
while most investment companies would be happy to see their 
investment funds grow bostonbased fidelity is concerned it 
believes many of the new investors some of whom pulled money out 
of other safer fidelity mutual funds dont know what theyre 
getting into 
right now there is a misperception about what drives the 
performance of these securities said litvack fidelitys vice 
president of marketing interest rates are not the primary driver 
of these funds its much more a function of the economy 
with investmentgrade bonds declining interest rates usually 
lead to higher bond prices thats because bonds keep paying the 
same fixed interest while rates available elsewhere are becoming 
less attractive 
but junkbond traders are more concerned about the financial 
health of the companies that issued the bonds if the economy sours 
these companies would be at risk of not earning enough to pay the 
interest on the bonds or even of outright default 
a lot of these junk bonds havent been tested in a down 
market said brian s mattes a spokesman for the vanguard group 
another major mutualfund operator 
there could be a stampede out of the fund in a recession he 
said there will be a lot of people running for the door at the 
same time in fact the price may go down more because of that 
vanguard has seen the assets of its junkbond fund grow 13 
percent in the past two months from about 114 billion at the end 
of april to about 129 billion last week some is from appreciation 
and the rest from new investors 
mattes said vanguard based in valley forge pa sent brochures 
to its customers to warn them of the risks of its junkbond fund 
it should not be viewed as a shortterm investment at all he 
said longterm investors would be at a lesser risk of losing 
principal because they could ride out an economic downturn 
investors expecting declining interest rates should put their 
money in treasury funds litvack said 
in fact total return on treasury bonds the total interest paid 
plus any change in the bond prices exceeded that of the 
higheryielding junk bonds in the first five months of this year 
the januarymay return on sevenyear treasury bonds exceeded 6 
percent while fidelitys junkbond fund returned only 226 percent 
and vanguards returned 212 percent due to major declines in the 
price of these bonds as the economy slowed according to lipper 
analytical services corp 
litvack said junkbond funds are not for investors saving for 
retirement or other needs 
one major mutualfund company dreyfus corp said it is so 
concerned about the risks of junkbond funds that it doesnt sponsor 
one 
the underlying basis for junk bonds is that economic expansion 
will continue forever enabling highly leveraged companies to meet 
their heavy debt burdens said howard stein dreyfus chairman and 
chief executive 
dreyfus he said is not that optimistic 
</TEXT>
